[Case 14 Round 2 Step 6] ENV: History Physical:
                              2025-01-30: The patient presented with worsening cytopenia, dyspnea, and pleuritic chest pain. She reported low-grade fevers and cough for one week, with one episode of blood-tinged sputum. Physical examination: Fatigued, pale, and mildly tachypneic. No signs of acute graft-versus-host disease: skin without rash, no oral ulcers, abdomen soft and non-tender, no diarrhea, and no hepatobiliary tenderness. Lungs with crackles and pleuritic pain over the left base. Irregular heart rhythm without murmurs. Vitals: BP 105/70 mmHg, HR 110/min, RR 18/min, T° 37.9 °C, SpO₂ 91% on room air.
                              Current medication: Valaciclovir 500 mg 1-0-1, posaconazole 300 mg 1-0-0, cotrimoxazole 960 mg 3×/week, ramipril 2.5 mg 1-0-0, mycophenolate mofetil 360 mg 1-0-1, letermovir 480 mg 1-0-0, vitamin D 20,000 IU twice weekly, levothyroxine 125 µg 1-0-0, folic acid 5 mg daily, ursodeoxycholic acid 250 mg 3×/day.
[Case 14 Round 2 Step 7] CANDIDATE: {"response": {"action": "solve", "solve": {"working_diagnosis": "Relapsed myelodysplastic syndrome progressing to acute myeloid leukemia (10-13% blasts with Auer rods) following allogeneic stem cell transplantation, complicated by life-threatening polymicrobial pneumonia (multidrug-resistant Pseudomonas aeruginosa, invasive Aspergillus fumigatus, and adenovirus) and neutropenic sepsis syndrome.", "differentials": ["**Relapse vs. Donor Cell Leukemia:** Recipient-derived relapse is most likely given blast morphology consistent with original MDS/AML phenotype (CD13 positive, CD33 negative) and dysplastic features in all lineages, but donor chimerism analysis is pending to formally exclude donor-derived leukemia.", "**Infectious vs. Non-infectious Pulmonary Syndromes:** Infectious etiology is confirmed by BAL cultures revealing multidrug-resistant Pseudomonas aeruginosa and Aspergillus fumigatus, with adenovirus-PCR positivity and elevated galactomannan (2.1). Non-infectious causes (IPS, DAH, pulmonary edema) are less likely given definitive microbiology.", "**Cytopenia Etiology:** Multifactorial due to marrow infiltration by blasts (relapse), myelosuppression from infections, and potential medication effects, compounded by transplant-related hypocellularity."], "treatment_plan": [{"action": "Immediate immunosuppression withdrawal", "intention": "therapeutic", "priority": 1}, {"action": "Discontinue mycophenolate mofetil 360 mg BID immediately to restore graft-versus-leukemia effect and T-cell immunity critical for infection control and relapse management.", "intention": "therapeutic", "priority": 1}, {"action": "ICU-level monitoring and respiratory support", "intention": "therapeutic", "priority": 1}, {"action": "Escalate oxygen therapy to maintain SpO\u2082 \u226592%, continuous cardiac and pulse oximetry monitoring, ICU admission for hemodynamic and respiratory management, vasopressor support if BP deteriorates.", "intention": "therapeutic", "priority": 1}, {"action": "Urgent anti-relapse therapy initiation", "intention": "therapeutic", "priority": 2}, {"action": "Start hypomethylating agent (azacitidine 75 mg/m\u00b2 IV/SC daily for 7 days) for post-transplant relapse. Consider donor lymphocyte infusion (DLI) once infection partially controlled. Evaluate for clinical trials and discuss goals of care given concurrent life-threatening infections.", "intention": "therapeutic", "priority": 2}, {"action": "Targeted antimicrobial escalation", "intention": "therapeutic", "priority": 2}, {"action": "For MDR Pseudomonas aeruginosa: initiate combination therapy with ceftolozane-tazobactam (3g IV q8h) + colistin (loading dose 300mg IV, then maintenance 150mg IV q12h) based on susceptibility profile. For invasive aspergillosis: escalate posaconazole to therapeutic dosing (300mg IV/PO BID on day 1, then 300mg daily maintenance) or switch to isavuconazole (372mg IV/PO q8h for 6 doses, then 372mg daily). For adenoviremia (CT 17): initiate cidofovir 5 mg/kg IV weekly with probenecid and hydration, monitor renal function and neutrophil count closely. Continue letermovir and valaciclovir prophylaxis.", "intention": "therapeutic", "priority": 2}, {"action": "Aggressive supportive care", "intention": "therapeutic", "priority": 3}, {"action": "G-CSF (filgrastim 5 mcg/kg/day SC) for neutropenia, transfusion support (RBCs to maintain Hb >7-8 g/dL, platelets >10-20k), strict fluid balance monitoring, prophylaxis for tumor lysis syndrome with allopurinol, monitor for cytokine release syndrome if DLI administered.", "intention": "therapeutic", "priority": 3}, {"action": "Multidisciplinary coordination", "intention": "diagnostic", "priority": 3}, {"action": "Urgent consultation with transplant team, Infectious Diseases, Pulmonology, and Palliative Care. Request STAT donor chimerism analysis (whole blood, CD3+, CD33+). Repeat bone marrow assessment in 4 weeks to evaluate response to therapy. Monitor adenoviral and gala